  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - SHADOWKNIGHT</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>USE IT ALL</font> - <small>Soultravel, Ayonae Ro</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><p>Playing an SK is a challenge. It is probably the 2nd most
active class in the game after a bard. You have to keep pet in
line, taunt, bash, use bow and use spells, switch weapons, etc.
You need to keep moving. If you aren't doing something, something
is wrong (or you're out of mana).<br>
<br>
Quick word on races: Ogres are the best, but the hardest to lvl.
Troll and Iksar regen become obsolete, humans and erudites are
blind and along with DEs cant bash with 2Hers. Ogres are
difficult to stun from the front--this is key for casting in
combat. If you want fast levels, play a DE, but if you have
powerleveling possibilities, I strongly suggest an Ogre.<br>
<br>
By this point in the game, everyone knows how to fear kite, so Im
not going to explain it. If you need to know how to do it, read
the other guides--although I think it's pretty obvious. Ill
include a quick level guide followed by some strategy tips. This
guide is designed for fast solo exp with key faction advances and
some group possibilities.<br>
<br>
Quick level guide assuming a fair amount of twinkage:<br>
<br>
lvl 1 - 7 noob areas, maybe NRo at 5-7.<br>
lvl 8 - 12 orc camps in EC, yes theyre crowded. Theyre crowded
for a reason. There are better places for exp, but the faction
you can get here is nice. If youre bored at 11, try dervs.<br>
lvl 13 - 16 Orcs or Crocs in oasis<br>
lvl 16 - 20 HH--again the faction is important. This is a
critical spot for non teleporters and its good to get faction
here.<br>
lvl 20 - 23 Overthere nooby zone<br>
lvl 23 - 30 Lake of Ill Omen (can also do giants in warsliks if
you dont mind the run).<br>
lvl 31 - 35 FM<br>
lvl 35 - 42 OT<br>
lvl 43 - 50 DL - Karnors (watch faction)<br>
Depending on your lvl of twinkage, or your ability to find
groups, those levels can shift a bit, but all those spots are
great for their lvls.<br>
<br>
Strategy tips:<br>
<br>
Group and taunt. With the increase in group bonus, grouping is
good. Keep your taunt skill up--it can save your butt by saving
your cleric or your pet (some SKs have difficulty distinguising
the two). Also keep your Abjuration skill maxed using endure cold
spell--very important for feign death at 30. (I wish someone had
told me this before lvl 23).<br>
<br>
Always taunt for your pet. Your pet is not worthless. He will do
a nice bit of damage starting at lvl 9 as long as you can keep
him alive. The trick to this is taunting for him. Keep the
monsters on you unless you're fleeing. I suggest putting pet on
/pet guard here, /pet notaunt. If you are twinked out badly
enough, pet may not be worth the effort, but it can do some
damage. Outdoors only, of course.<br>
<br>
When soloing, range is your friend. SKs have a lot of range
posibilities. They can open up with bow fire, and they have many
spells to use at range. If soloing, (and youll hear some
arguments on this but theyre wrong), I suggest opening with
snare. Doing this gives you more time before the monster gets to
you. You should be able to get 2 spells and 2 bow shots off
before monster hits you. Snare, fire bow while spells are
recovering, dot/drain strength/fear depending on your situation,
bow again, lifetap. It's nice having the monster down a good 50
hp and dotted before he gets a shot at you.<br>
<br>
Group with druids and rangers. Although SKs can snare, our snare
doesnt last nearly as long as a ranger's or druid's. If you can
team with one of these that can snare, you can concentrate on
fear fear fear and hardly take any damage. (But our snare is a
dot!) I dont care. That dot is at least 9 levels lower than its
effectiveness. You and your druid/ranger friend will have no
trouble with damage, and you will conserve massive amounts of
mana, because 1. your dot/snare gets resisted alot, and 2. needs
to be recast. 3. your friend wont have to heal you as much. When
grouped with my ranger pal, I end up using my heal to keep his hp
up (he does the pulling). <br>
<br>
Escapability: SKs have great escapability. Try to always keep a
sow potion on you for this to make it even better. First line of
defense will obviously be feign. 2nd, pet. 3rd, shadow step if
you can keep the spell handy. Shadow step/sow from potion works
well. Harm can also be used as last resort.<br>
<br>
Damage: The key to dishing out damage with an SK is using all of
your options. Our damage is piecemeal. We do mediocre weapon
damage in comparison to dual wielding classes. But, we can bash,
we can cast lifedraw, we have a pet, we can dot, we can fire
bows. And to top it all off, we can harm. If you don't use it,
you lose it.<br>
<br>
Harm touch: I urge you not to use this skill casually. The key to
HT is having it when you need it. Dont get caught up in having to
use it once per day. It can save your butt if you have it when
that mob just seems to have your number, or when the sarnak wont
taunt off your cleric and there are 3 more on your back. Again,
the key to making HT effective is timing.<br>
<br>
</p>
</td></tr>
